Db2 Operator, especially on OpenShift, typically relies not only on storage but potentially on other core cluster operators:

Possible Dependencies and Issues:

1. Cluster Storage Operator (CSO):
Db2 relies heavily on PVC/PV functionality. If the original NFS deletion triggered issues with storage operator components, it might still be in a degraded or error state.

Check quickly:

oc get co storage
oc describe co storage


2. CSI or Storage Driver Operators:
If your cluster uses a CSI-based NFS provisioner or other external storage drivers, ensure they are running and not degraded:

oc get pods -n openshift-cluster-csi-drivers
oc get pods -n openshift-storage
oc get pods -n kube-system


3. Node Health and Operator:
Since you moved storage from worker to infra nodes, verify infra nodes are healthy and labeled correctly, and that workloads are allowed there.

oc get nodes -l node-role.kubernetes.io/infra
oc describe node <infra-node-name>


4. Operator Lifecycle Manager (OLM):
Db2 operator installation and CRDs management rely on OLM. If something corrupted namespaces or CRDs, the OLM may face issues.

Check:

oc get co operator-lifecycle-manager
oc get pods -n openshift-operator-lifecycle-manager
oc get pods -n openshift-marketplace




---

Recommended actions to rule out wider cluster issues quickly:

1. Verify Cluster Operator Health:

oc get co

Make sure all operators are in the Available=True and Degraded=False state.


2. Check Events in the openshift- namespaces:*

oc get events -A | grep -iE 'error|failed|unable|mount'


3. Check CRDs and Operator Subscriptions health:

oc get subscriptions,operatorgroups,installplans -A
